{
  "texts": [
    "This small sample size per condition might lead to under-powered and less sensitive studies, as participants are not used as their own controls and individual differences might influence results and their interpretation.",
    "In this context, only large effect sizes might be detected.",
    "For these reasons, it is important to check the required sample size a priori using expected power, alpha, and effect size.",
    "The sample size might therefore depend on the design of the study (a within-participants design would require fewer participants than a between-participants design) and the expected effect size.",
    "Leichtmann and Nitsch (2020a) argue that replication difficulties are based on a lack of theory and transparency, and the use of methodologies that are not powerful enough."
  ]
}